ers were mostly Democratic as the decade began, Republicans eagerly exploited alternative media opportunities. Using the stereopticon (a modernized magic lantern), they developed the first campaign documentaries. Soon they were exploiting motion pictures, the phonograph, and telephone in surprising and often successful ways. Brimming with rich historical details, Musser’s remarkable tale reveals the political forces driving the emergence of modern media.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aMass mediaxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aPolitical campaignszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aPresidentszUnited StatesxElectionxHistoryy19th century. 0aPresidentszUnited StatesxElectionsxHistoryy19th century. 0aPress and politicszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aamerican history.  acampaigning.  ademocracy.  ademocrat.  adigital native.  adigital world.  aelection.  amedia.  amodern media.  amodern world.  amulti media.  anew york.  anewspaper.  aonline.  apolitical party.  apresident.  apresidential campaign.  apresidential candidate.  arepublican.  arunning for president.  aswing state.  atrue story.  aunited states history.  aunited states.  aus history.  avictory.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831106675470 cprintz978052029272740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520966123?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520966123423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520966123/original  a978-3-11-066754-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY